docs.lead_paragraph: Board of Councilmen. The Board of Councilmen met on Friday, the President, C. H. HASWELL, in the Chair. Several Petitions and resolutions were presented and referred. Among the former was one from Dr. Salter asking permission to place Hiram Powers' statue of WASHINGTON in the Governor's Room, City Hall.

docs.lead_paragraph: Much indignation is expressed at ORR'S arrangement of the Select Committee on Kansas. Not only has he given the Lecomptonites a majority, thus vlolating the parliamentary custom, but has totally disregarded the wishes of the Anti-Lecomptonites, and composed the minority of the Committee very weakly. In view of the closeness of the vote, however, no attempts will be made to force a reconstruction.

docs.lead_paragraph: The President's levee on Tuesday evening was attended by an immense throng. The Star says: "The President was looking in fine health, and apparently quite recovered from his late cold and hoarseness. The presentations to him were made as usual by MARSHALL HOOVER, and those to Miss LANE by Commissioner BLAKE.

docs.lead_paragraph: The screw-steamship City of Baltimore, from Liverpool at about 91/2 A. M. on the 27th day of January, arrived at this port yesterday morning. The City of Baltimore brings advices of the same date as those received by the Indian. Nothing further of importance had been developed in regard to the recent attempt to assassinate the Emperor.

docs.lead_paragraph: This has been an eventful day-and the faithful band of patriots who stood together this morning in resisting the precipitate consummation of the crime against Kansas, have succeeded, in all probability, In averting the horrors of civil war. I have little to add to my dispatch upon this subject, beyond a comment or two In relation to the course of the New-York delegation. Not amen of them all is In favor of the Lecompton scheme.
